I cried too. It's been hard staying socially isolated during COVID19, especially because my grandmother passed away a couple of nights ago. I had a little moment in shavasana where my fingers met above my head, and they just held on to each other, like you would hold the hand of a friend who was going through a tough time. It felt so sweet and loving, like I just appreciated how nurturing I am, and how I'm glad to be going through this with...me. Weird I know. I guess I just felt glad that I can take care of myself in little ways. Thank you Adriene for providing a safe space for practice, and facilitating development of my emotional, physical, spiritual, mental and cognitive health. Thank you Thank you.

Adriene...allow me to first thank you for doing what you do! I am a stay-at-home Dad, and I homeschool our daughter (15) and son (13). At the start of each school day, we have a yoga session, followed by our meditative practice, and then journalling, before we even begin any of our "required" studies. We actually alternate between a "flow style" yoga and Yin yoga...so, it took us 10 weeks to complete your 30 Day Challenge, which we just finished today! Now on to "Yoga Camp".
On a more personal note, I suffered a severe spinal injury when I was 30 years old...almost 8 years ago. I was initially  paralyzed from the waist down due to a rare complication called Cauda Equina Syndrome. I suffered through 7 years of various surgeries, procedures, physical therapy, pain management, and loads of narcotics. A few months ago, I decided to take responsibility for my own well-being, and made many changes to my life. The first step was stopping the pain meds...those 30+ days were an absolute nightmare! I started walking every morning...I know get up at 4am and walk 6 miles each and every day. But...I must say, that aside from my Dharma practice and meditative practice, yoga really saved my life! 
My "little" sister, who is now 25, has practiced yoga since high school, and she recommended your videos to me....I was immediately hooked by your warmth and kind spirit, and the rest is history! 
So...keep doing what you're doing...you may not realize it, or think about it often, but you are changing lives!
Namaste...
Ryan
I finally did it! After two failed attempts, I finally buckeled down and did all 30 days. <3

Well, I did it!  It took about 35 days, but I freaking did it.  This is the first time I've committed to & completed something for an entire month (other than poor life choices, of course LOL).  Next up? 30 days of TRUE -  Here I come!

Finished this today, amidst the Covid-19 lockdown. Everything else in my world currently, is uncertain, but this is one thing I stuck with this every, single, day since I began on March 27th. Words are not enough to thank you for this, Adriene. I'm not known for my ability to 'finish' things and I'm in a bit of a shock to have reached here. Can't wait to continue this journey with you. 
Lots of love from India,
Neha

After the video ended, and as I write this, tears are streaming down my face. It's hard to explain how much I wanted to complete 30 Days of Yoga. Not only to feel better inside and out, but to prove to myself that I am capable of disciplining myself and committing to something.  Adriene, thank you!

OMG I absolutely just went for it today! I've never sweated so much on this challenge.  Occasionally I would look down at the video and you were doing the same thing as me; which totally encouraged me to keep going.  I set out on this challenge to help my insomnia and to loosen my back a little. I was in a bad car accident 10 years ago and have suffered from back pain every day since. I have tried physiotherapy, massages, you name it and I never even considered Yoga. Well, I have slept like a baby the past 30 nights and for the first time in 10 years my back hasn't hurt once during this journey. Thank you so much Adriene and the community for this challenge. I feel so much stronger as a person and in my body.  I can touch my toes for the first time ever and I can actually savour the moment rather than rushing through life.  I have looked forward to getting on my mat each and every day and time seems to stop when I'm on it. I shall be doing this challenge for another 30 days so I can fine tune my technique then I'll venture off on my own and see how I do.  Congratulations to everyone who made it this far!! I have been telling all my friends and family about it so I'm sure you'll see them here pretty soon! A huge Namaste to you all!!!!! ^______^

I'm reading the comments and I'm getting so emotional. Having the same feelings as you my friends , being proud, happy and grateful, makes me feel well surrounded by you! Even if we don't know each other, our souls are connected somehow. I can feel your energy, this beautiful energy . And yess we made it this far and it feels great! 
The 20mins of yoga were my best part of the day during these 30 days, confined at home because of the coronavirus but I am very happy to discover you dear friend Adriene !

From now On, I am the one who is going to be in control of myself, not the weight machine. I‚Äôm going to be 26 soon and I‚Äôm switching to healthy life style gradually for the sake of my skin, body and my beautiful brain. Thank you Adrienne!‚ù§Ô∏è

Something about you and the attitude you bring and help me bring to the mat, it's so inspiring and empowering. Full journey comment thread is on the Day 1 video:) [Day 30/30]

Day 30 - Journey complete.  Since Day 1 I had looked forward to this moment, but now I don't wanna go.  Every single day for 30 days straight I came back to this series.  Reading people's comments, seeing how others felt so far, being part of a wholesome online community.  And now it's done.  This video was a perfect passing of the baton of trust.  Adriene allowing us to have complete freedom, to implement anything and everything we've learned so far and to make this video unique to each and every one of us.  Despite never really talking with people in the comments section, I do hope passersby have seen my day by day commentary in hope to feel some form of motivation, connection and relation to keep pulling through.  I hope passersby will read this in days, weeks, months or years to come.  I hope passersby ensure that the end of this journey does not mean the end of Yoga!  I'm going to miss the 'new challenge' aura of this playlist and how this series helped me look forward to something everyday, especially during lockdown.  I hope Adriene reads this.  Thank you Adriene for making an average person like me find a new appreciation for Yoga, for guiding a complete newbie and nurturing me the past 30 days and for helping me fix my back and hip flexors.  I'll miss this.
I am so proud of myself and everyone who took part and finished. Completing this has given me a new lease of life, fitness, flexibility and  such a loving community to be a part of.

I cheated.¬† Yup, sure did.¬† When the downloadable version came through a few days ago, I peaked to see what you had in mind for Day 30.¬†¬† Yikes!¬† Panic!¬† Freak Out!¬† You mean you have to do this myself?!¬†¬† But this morning, the fear and apprehension was gone.¬† I simply hopped on the mat and let it flow, trusting myself to Find What Feels Good.¬† It felt wonderful!!!¬†¬† I found a calm, peaceful, easy practice within me¬†full of mountain poses where I stretched/looked/arched towards the sky.¬†¬† Very uplifting. ¬†The number of heart openers surprised me.¬†A few hip openers and forward folds¬†too.¬†¬†Not a lot of planks, though, which I grew to love.¬† I was still flowing when the music stopped.¬† So I continued on.¬† I see it now -- for the last 30 days¬†you have been building us towards this moment, empowering us to trust ourselves.¬† Thank you and Namaste.¬† (PS¬† the music was fantastic --- strong and empowering)

I Thank you with my whole heart Adriene, I started this yoga journey after a severe panic attack took over me before a job interview (which I couldn't build the strength within myself to go to) as someone who has never having taken part in yoga before or dedicated myself entirely to something I made myself a promise, to stick to this challenge for some stability and a sense of constant for my mind and who knew that 30 days later I couldn‚Äôt imagine my day without rolling out my mat.


I journaled every day after my practise and today reflecting on my journey shows me how much I‚Äôve grown.
Today I wrote ‚ÄúI wish I could put this feeling in a bottle and carry with me always, finishing this 30 day journey guiding my own practise gave me an overwhelming sense of presence, pride and power within myself‚Äù 


This morning, The 30th day of this beautiful practise I received a call after a job interview to say I‚Äôd been offered a full time position - for a job I didn‚Äôt think I was good enough for. 


It was meant to be - I now know I can go into my new job with a smile and use my breath as an anchor to stabilise any anxious feelings.


So thank you, you are changing lives. You certainly helped me find my light again. Namaste.

Today I was just tired and didn't know if I could make it through the practice without your loving and helpful guidance. But I tried and did it! I'll be coming back for more of your videos but thank you so much for giving me the tools to do yoga on my own!!

edit: I forgot to mention my heels both touched the mat in downward facing dog for the first time today! I was so hyped!

it's hard to put into words how much this has meant to me. i actually started with low expectations, simply because i didn't know what to expect, and 30 days of yoga came into my life in a moment when i was ready to simply say "yes" without overthinking or taking time to build up a huge fear of failing. each day it has meant more and more...some days the practice came and went and the movement was good for my body, and other days i descended into shavasana with tears inexplicably rolling out the corners of my eyes. release...relief...rebirth...yeah, all the typical yogi feelings :) i, like many others, had a few moments of panic when you said you were un-mic-ing and i figured i'd have to be fixated on the video the entire time to know what the hell to do next. suprisingly, and delightfully, i almost didn't watch at all, and how precious the moments when i'd glance over and see we were doing the same thing. thank you so much for making all of this (and more) possible...for me, and for so many others.¬†
I love this! My favorite part: hearing the complete song you use for the intro :‚Äô) thanks

This has been, and especially today exhilarating!!!  I choose to follow you and moving to your pace shot electrifying energy through my body. Thank you thank you thank you!  Namaste Namaste Namaste!!!  üíñüôèüéâ

I hate New Year's resolutions! But 30 days ago, I committed to yoga practice with you every day. I am a 53 (gosh, almost 54)-year-old massage therapist. Two months ago, I had carpal tunnel surgery on both hands, and every day was torture. Not because of the surgery, but because I was forced to stop doing what I love. I began your series as part of my rehab. On Day One, I couldn't weight-bear with my hands on the floor for more than a few seconds. Every time you brought us to plank, tears came to my eyes. But your encouragement kept me focused on doing what I CAN do, and each day I saw improvement. I just finished day 30, complete with plank for a full minute and THREE pushups!!! Thank you, Adriene, for helping me get back to what I love.

I am here. I finally made it to the 30th day in April 2020. Adriene, thank you from the bottom of my crying, grateful heart for putting this practice out there. On the first day was the first time I ever dared to do yoga. I didn't have a mat and didn't buy one immediately because I didn't trust myself to stick to it. But I did. Because your voice guided me with love, kindness, compassion, stillness and jokes. This practice has led me through a break up, my childhood traumas, through my body shaming past and I am truly grounded in this moment as I write, glowing with gratitude. In the last few days as I was quarantined (still continue to be), I have turned to your videos in the middle of the night and hopped on my mat, cried till I felt everything was out and followed your gentle voice. This practice means the world to me. Thank you so much :') Sending you immense amount of love all the way from India.

I just finished Day 30 today! I'm incredibly happy with myself and other people I've told about your channel were super impressed. :) Now I plan to get into your foundations of yoga videos so I can learn how to do the postures correctly. Thanks for this it really helped me so much.

Thank you Adriene. I can not express in words how grateful I am for what you do & for bringing yoga into my life. You are wonderful! My humble salutations to you. To keep finding what feels good, lots of love- Bhavin

Thank you for the time you spend empowering others.

Omg omg guess what I finished 30 days of yoga in 30 days and what a difference, for someone who could barely walk properly to now balancing in tree pose , I‚Äôm proud of myself , on to August reunite 2019 and yoga camp for 30 days , should of done this years ago , what a life changer , thank you Adriene namaste üôè

Adrienne, I couldn't leave this 30 day challenge without saying thank you. A few days before I first began I had experienced my first panic attack (I have always been a worry-wart but it got kind of out of control). I prayed that the Lord would teach me to control my thoughts and remove me from the path I was on of constant worry and negativity in my head. I was searching the internet for different ways to control what you allow in your head.. and I read a comment from someone who said "you need to try 30 days with Adrienne, it's life changing". That was one of the best decisions I have ever made was coming here to your page. You taught me to control my breath... and with that, I realized you can control what goes on inside. You taught me that I don't come here on my mat to compare myself with others, but to be here now and to be present and to listen to my OWN body. This last day was so fitting... but, even if I had it on mute with my own music playing, I still heard you say "plant your foot, who cares if you can't do it be wherever you are, be weird, and (my favorite one) smile!". Thank you so much Adrienne, seriously. I have not had one attack since I've started, and yes of course things still come into my head that are negative but I breath them right back out. See ya over at Yoga Boot Camp!!!!!!!
I finished it thanks it helped me so so much  now I will going to the 31 days of yoga

Felt quite emotional with this one. I used your video as a guide but did some of my own of what I've learned. I finally did the CROW! I need to try Yoga Camp next. I never thought Yoga would actually make me feel calm and time flies while doing it!

Sad it's over but excited to jump into my own practice - I just went free today and found when I looked at the screen we sometimes crossed paths; that was fun! Today was freeing, I was scared to just do my own thing at first, like I'd forgotten it all - funny how you just know what to do when ¬†you settle in. Breath came easily and I followed it through. Thanks for the journey giiiirl! x
this is the first workout challenge i've ever completed! i'm proud of myself. thank you for putting this videos out into the world <3
I did it! Started about 6 months ago. Took a very long pause but picked it back up and managed to complete the last video on the last day of the year.
It may have taken me longer than 30 Days, but I did it! Thank you so much for all of this, Adriene. I look forward to tackling Yoga Camp next!

Dear Adriene, yoga gave me so much. And for everyone out there starting out, I just wanna tell you all the benefits of yoga I've experienced in just 26 days (I started 30daysofyoga 4 days late):

1) My health has improved so much in all ways. No more headaches, no more pain in my stomach or anywhere in the body. No more back pain. No more weakness and exhaustion.
2) I feel more positive. On some days, yoga has been the highlight of my day and just the best part of it. It saved me.
3) I've learned how to forgive myself. I don't feel so negative about myself or my body and I don't punish myself whenever I eat something I like. I found time for ME.
4) It has helped me to lose weight. I don't have weight problems but my skin looks prettier and my body just looks better and more firmed.
5) My posture! My shoulders are relaxed almost all the time and my posture is wonderful, and my moves.
6) I do not stress as much. During the exams, that was what I needed - something to keep my mind off of studying but to help me improve my focus as well.
7) I sleep better, I eat better, I do things for myself that help me grow as a person.
8) I can do some cool poses right now and I'm so excited about it! By doing yoga, you feel the¬† results so fast.
9) It keeps me sane and happy.

Dear Adriene, I completed this in 40 days instead of 30 because of the many time I felt sick out of burnout and fatigue. But then I realized that perhaps, it was meant to be for me to complete it in 40 days since where I live, there's this cultural belief that it takes 40 days for a dying soul to depart and it takes 40 days for a newborn to receive their soul.  And in a way that's how I felt at the end of this video - like that part of me who just couldn't let loose has departed and I have this new soul that's ready to be more attuned to how I feel. 


Today, I only followed you in the beginning and the rest of the way I closed my eyes and basically had a conversation with myself. The entire video, my mind was saying things like "ooh, let's do a tree pose" or "okay, I feel like doing a vinyasa" and my body responded. I was smiling the whole way through and in my mind, it was just like "see, told you this would be fun, told you that you're strong enough to hold this teaser" and things like that. I never imagined that I could listen to myself that well. It's still a work in progress to completely accept myself and tune in to that voice inside, but hey, that's what a newborn does right? It grows. Thank you for guiding me to unlock this light in me, Adriene. You are a blessing. Namaste!

Thank you so much Adriene for bringing your energy and your enthusiasm to the world, in particular through this 30 Days series.  I just completed it and ok, I confess, I cheated a little along the way, I missed some days here and there but I always came back to it.  I'm glad I did.  I suppose you could say it all lead up to my first true Yoga experience.   I loved the idea that you came up with for the 30th day although I was a little apprehensive at first.  I felt like Bambi to be honest, standing for the first time!

I started out with a crossed leg position which is unusual for me since it's uncomfortable but it's what I felt like I should do.  Then I saw you did the same.  As I would do some stretches, you would do the same stretches and I was like "wow, I'm doing it right!".  Then I went to Cat-Cow and you moved to all fours, so then I was thinking, "Yeah, I've got this!".  Gradually as the video progressed I found I was looking less and less, and then I looked at one point to see we were doing totally different things and I was okay with it.  I was thinking "Look at me ma! I'm a big boy now!". :D

Then I started to wind down and prepare for the corpse pose and by this time I was in the zone but I just was suddenly overcome with emotion.  I suppose you could call it a catharsis.  It was sad and happy and moving.  At which point, I look up to see the video drawing to a close.  Such a fitting end to a wonderful journey, so I thank you again for sharing this and helping me to take better care of my body and my mind.

Keep up the good work!

I started this 30 days series a couple of weeks after quarantine started. I had finally started going regularly to the gym months prior to the pandemic, and started taking yoga classes there. I was devastated when I realized I couldn't continue 'cause I had been enjoying it so much, so I decided to try it online. However, yoga during quarantine proved to be a bigger challenge than I thought. Not being able to go out to practice yoga with other people and to get feedback from the instructor, not having the same routines for eating, sleeping and going to university/work, the increased stress and constant fear that this whole situation put me (and all of us) in. It all seemed to hinder my ability to actually enjoy, relax and concentrate in the practice, and even getting to the mat everyday was a struggle. So, after a week, I stopped. I felt totally defeated, I was so disappointed at myself. 

I've learned and grown so much during this period though. There's been some really tough days, some rough periods, but it's all left me feeling stronger and more determined. A couple of weeks ago I decided to try this challenge again, with a renewed attitude and energy. I am proud to say that yesterday I was able to finish it!!! I wanted to cry of happiness. And a HUGE part of this success is also due to Adriene's positive, warm, motivated attitude. This whole process has left me feeling inspired and excited to continue with this wonderful practice. You are an amazing instructor, Adriene, and I will definitely continue watching and learning along with your videos, even after this whole pandemic situation finally comes to an end! Thank you, from the bottom of my heart.
Wow, what a beautiful experience this was. Thank you for your nurturing knowledge Adrienne :)

March 2020 checking in- started march 1st, today is march 31st (but it's 3:25 am and I'm a night owl who does her yoga before bed)
I've developed strength, breath control, flexibility, balance, etc but i'm most pleased with the off the mat gains I've made.
I cried during this last session, I wasn't sure I could do my own routine so I started off meditating cris-cross like Adriene, and I thought about how difficult this month has been. I started a new job, my favorite event of the year was cancelled due to COVID-19, and I received all my college decisions (with many rejections). And through all of that, I stuck to this, it wasn't always easy but it wasn't hard either. i don't consider myself to be a committed or routine person but I somehow managed and I'm glad I did.


I was able to listen to my body and do what I needed this last session. I think I may restart the thirty days for April because I couldn't even hold my attempt at downward dog for more than two seconds at the beginning of the month.


My final note is that for a multitude of reason I went off/had to go off my antidepressants ( i tried a new sleep medication and needed to avoid complications. Usually when I go off my meds, I cry almost daily, I get overwhelmed easily, I struggle to see all the light in the world. I don't think yoga cures depression as I haven't been severely depressed in over a year but I have no doubt in my mind that yoga has helped with my emotional well being and stability.

Continuing to explore the yoga/taekwondo connection: This concept of "melting the thighs" inward or outward, depending on the posture being built, piqued my interest as I was working through the "Fundamentals" series. Being mindful of this helped direct the energy of where the posture was "going," and aligned the joints so as to minimize stress; also solidified the connection from the feet and ankles up through to the hips. This morning, as I performed my taekwondo poomse (patterns or forms), I paid attention to the rotation of the thigh muscles in various movements. Forward stances seem to benefit from melting the thighs inward to provide stability and generate power to the fists. Back stances seem to "want" outward rotation to stabilize the knee/ankle connections. When executing kicks, the standing leg seems to prefer outward rotation, as if it were "opening the gate" for the kicking leg to move freely. I look at photos of world class soccer players and notice that the thigh of the standing leg, as it plants next to the ball, rotates outward before the kicking leg delivers its payload. This can't be coincidence! Young martial artists are taught to focus on the hips as they perform the various strikes and blocks, while the thighs just sort of "hang" there. The result can be a frustrating disconnect throughout the entire skeletal frame as we try to FORCE our bodies into the correct posture. Mindfulness of the thigh rotation seems now like a no-brainer, seeing as it contains the largest muscle groups. Fascinating!

Dear Adriene! I have so much to say, not even sure where to start. After 3 weeks of practicing I had my double wisdom tooth removal so I had to take a 1 week break during the program but I wasn't afraid at all, I knew that when my teeth let me, I'll take on from where I left. And I did. Today is the last day of my first yoga with Adrienne 30 days program and I cannot thank you enough for bringing me the joy of practicing. Also I started the program like it is impossible for me to do it 30 days in a row due to time schedule issues, I also knew that my birthday will be during the program and I will probably drink some alcohol that day so no way I will practice on my birthday. I did:) Got up really early just because I did not want to skip a day, drank almost nothing because I knew I will do the practice next day too and I don't wanna be hangover at all. That was the moment I knew this time is really different! I hope my message finds you, I really am thankful for every possible positive effects in my life, I also hope that other people who are struggling with similar issues than me will read my message and If it helps at least one person it's truly amazing. Hi Adrienne. I just want to thank you for your inspiration and your compassion which you magically have managed to make me feel across the Atlantic and out through my screen. Objectively this is one-way communication to thousands of people, but somehow you make me feel the love. It took me 6 months to get through...! But it has been part of a recovery since I broke my leg badly a year ago, went through surgery, laid still in a hospital bed for a week, went through surgery again, got home on crouches which I had to use for four months, still waiting for the skin to heal for another month. Before I broke my leg I didn't do much exercise being a typical full time working mom thinking chocolate was the only real treat, so you can imagine that what little strength and flexibility I had had was now completely gone. Struggling with daily tension headache, tendinitis in one shoulder and of cause still pains and swelling in the right leg, I startet seeing a physiotherapist twice a week. And after a couple of months he recommended I checked out your videos to continue the training on my own. And so I did :-) Three to four times a week I have used this 30-days program, going back and fourth, repeating my favorite sessions or just choosing what I had the time or energy for on that day, but never starting a new video without having done all the videos before that. And so today I finally made it. Because of your always including and compassionate comments, and reminding me to think of why I started this, I never felt like it was wrong or not good enough. It was just what suited me, and I never felt like giving up. I now feel strong, balanced and empowered, thanks to your great support - through YouTube-videos, who would have thought it :-) <3

Day 30. Originally I started this just as a warm up to help me start exercising again. I wanted to start calisthenics and B-girl dance challenges and strengthen my body in the process but the calisthenics and B-girl channels I subscribed to had exercises that were just too difficult for my level of fitness at the time, and some of the exercises I did were hurting my back (a sign of poor form and poor posture). I didn't give up on the calisthenics plan, but I decided to take baby steps toward achieving my goals and decided to look for yoga instead, for it actually helped me before in correcting my posture and in giving me a more positive outlook on life. I had come across this channel once or twice before and done a few exercises, and seen the 30 days of yoga challenge, and done the first one (and maybe more, I'm not sureüòâ) but I decided to come back and give it a try, hoping that by the end of the 30 day challenge my body would be strong enough and I would be more aware of proper spatial positioning to be able to train and start Chris Heria' s calisthenics program. üòÇ 
Now a little information about me: I STRUGGLE to continue with achieving my goals. It's not to say I've never done it, but that it's difficult for me to have the discipline sometimes to devote myself to something. And THANKFULLY that's changing. This year, and the previous one have been life-changing for me. I'm only 18, but I felt I was in the midst of an existential crisis. I didn't know where to begin or what to do, and for a while I was struggling to take some time for myself (I'd already begun to truly love and respect myself but I wasn't giving myself enough time to sit down and think or be POSITIVE and count my blessings).
I AM SO GRATEFUL TO HAVE COME ACROSS THIS CHANNEL.
I have become much more positive. I've been dedicating MUCH MORE of my time to accomplishing the goals I set out to achieve, and doing things the right way. I loved myself before, but I really have GROWN aware of myself and the beautiful things I have stored up inside me. I've grown stronger, happier, and more confident! I've embraced the inner child and will carry that little girl around with me for the rest of my days, and the coolest thing is that this is only the beginning! I've dedicated myself to completing the 30 days of yoga with Adrienne, and I'll be dedicating myself more not JUST in yoga (I'm a loyal YWA subscriber, haha) but in LIFE. With every ounce gratitude I have I thank you for the lovely encouraging journey I've gotten to take with this channel and with all the other brave and dedicated souls who have journeyed with me and made it this far. THANK YOU ALL!! üòäüíÉüèæüé∂NAMASTE üíúüíúüíúüòÉü§©üíúüíúüíú

It took me more than 30 days, as a few others have noted, but I did the whole thing and it's honestly been amazing. I've dabbled in yoga since high school, but never really committed to anything until this practice. I did a few of the beginner videos, and a couple of the foundations as well, before starting this. After day 2, I thought I'd struggle through the whole thing forever. And I kind of did, but not in the worst way possible, if that makes any sense. It's difficult to do some poses or transitions with a big belly, or with a bad knee, or with a sensitive ankle, or what have you. Sometimes it's frustrating because you get a little behind and then you struggle to rush to catch up. But eventually, it just kind of clicks that you don't have to do the poses exactly the way Adriene does them (though it's obviously the goal!), you just have to do them in a way that's mindful and works for you. I haven't managed to get my leg all the way up from down dog to lunge yet, but I found ways to make it work for me, at least until I do it. And when I was able to knock a pose out in a way that felt great and looked similar to Adriene's, that was just icing on the cake. This is all a long-winded way of saying this whole thing was amazing and great and I'm so excited to start Yoga Camp! (but in a couple weeks, though, I think, I'm gonna spend some time with the foundation videos and just play with more stuff!) Thank you for making such wonderful videos, and thank you for just being such a light, Adriene!

As the days progressed though, a 25 min video went by in a flash, and I didn't find myself aching to get to the next move, something to distract me from my frantic thoughts. 30 days later and I still had moments in the practice where I had to actively calm my thoughts, but overtime I became so much more able to acknowledge my thoughts without judgment, and just kind of let them live. Physically I have found more flexibility (can get my heels down in downward dog), mentally I have found more calm, and spiritually I have found more peace. Thank you so much Adrienne for this practice and this challenge. My life has been changed for the better by it.

Adriene, I wanted to take a moment to thank you. As a high school wrestler, I never foresaw myself ever doing yoga. However, two and a half years ago I suffered a major concussion/spinal fracture injury wrestling that has left me with chronic pain and has taken me out of sports since. I've tried many different treatment programs, including two years of physical therapy, with no real success. However, the last 30 days (admittedly a few more than that... whoops) have completely changed my outlook on my recovery. Not only were the length of the sessions perfect for me getting back into physical activity, but your emphasis on accepting where your body was at in that moment was crucial in helping me take things slow as I am someone who is used to pushing myself beyond what is good for healing from an injury. My neck and head pain has significantly decreased. Recently, I touched my toes for the first time in years, a moment my family actually teared up about because it was my first win physically since my injury. I just graduated high school yesterday and am leaving way more optimistic about my future than before doing the 30 days of yoga.Thank you for everything. I look forward to continuing with your other videos.

I tried doing this program in summer 2015 then injured myself on day 10 and was unable to walk normally for almost 2 months. So this time, I was careful not to overdo it with my right knee and simply forwarded a few times during moves that strained my right knee too much. I tried multiple times after that summer to do this program again, but would always fall off the wagon after day 3 or 4. This time, I did it, but it took almost 2.5 months to complete. Today is May 25th, 2017... when I started this time around early March, I had very bad digestion problems that lasted more than 2 months, severe anxiety, and depression. I wasn't showering for a week at a time. I started seeing a therapist for the first time in more than a decade. I went to doctors and specialists for blood tests, colonoscopy, endoscopy, MRI, bone density tests, allergy tests... etc. Everything turned out normal. Last year I had an issue for 5 months where I couldn't sit for long periods and after doctors telling me it's likely an inflamed prostate, it turned out to be CPPS (chronic pelvic pain syndrome). Then last summer for 2 months I had a strange vertigo and off-balance feeling that was almost constant. I wanted to kill myself. Now I realize all these issues I've been having for years and years and getting worse have all been due to untreated stress and anxiety. Anti-anxiety meds had their own side-effects so I've stopped them now. My health has improved drastically in the last 1.5 months. It took me some time to get through this 30 day program because I was alternating between swimming and other body weight exercises and I was exercising 5 days a week rather than 7 as I didn't want to risk injuring myself like I had several times before when I'd go hardcore after long periods of sedentary living then doing the opposite. I took a long term view of my health this time - giving myself 1 year to get in shape rather than 2-3 months. I just want to say thank you Adrienne. This is actually the first workout program I have completed - though not in 30 days. I'm in the best shape physically and more importantly, mentally , than I have been in decades. Tomorrow is my last day at my well paid cushy comfortable boring corporate desk job I've been miserable at for over 2 years with barely a vacation. My unhappiness with work / career has been the primary cause of my anxiety and depression. I know it will be a difficult transition in the next few months as I move to a different city without a job and prepare for what I want to do next at early middle-age (I have no idea what it may be although needs to be in a more creative field), but this practice has helped me deal with difficulties much better than a few months ago, and I'm confident this time I'll be ok. On some level, you have been instrumental in saving my life during a very difficult time a few months ago when I felt I was losing my mind, my body, and thought I have some horrible disease. I can't thank you enough Adrienne! Namaste.
